The 4 metrics below will be used to evaluate the model.¶

The metrics are computed based on p99 accuracy

In [2]:
def metrics(y_true,y_pred):
    """
    I asess the accuarcy of the model based on the 4 metrics below, MAPE, RMSE,
    Mean absolute error and Mean bias
    """
    ape_ett=np.abs(y_true-y_pred)/y_true
    ape_ett=ape_ett[ape_ett< np.percentile(ape_ett,99)]
    print("MAPE",ape_ett.mean())

    sq_error_ett = (y_true-y_pred) ** 2
    sq_error_ett=sq_error_ett[sq_error_ett< np.percentile(sq_error_ett,99)]
    print("RMSE:",np.sqrt(sq_error_ett.mean()))

    abs_error_ett = abs(y_true-y_pred)
    abs_error_ett=abs_error_ett[abs_error_ett< np.percentile(abs_error_ett,99)]
    print("Mean absolute error:",abs_error_ett.mean())

    #bias
    ett_bias=y_true-y_pred
    ett_bias=ett_bias[ett_bias< np.percentile(ett_bias,99)]
    print("Mean Bias",ett_bias.mean())

Some simple feature transforms¶

  • Take the log of the taget variable i.e salary since this helps take care of exterme values.
  • Convert other contonous variables to have 0 mean 1 standard deveiation. Does'nt help much in tree based models, but no harm done.
In [13]:
train_data.loc[:,'milesFromMetropolis']=(train_data.milesFromMetropolis-np.mean(train_data.milesFromMetropolis))/np.std(train_data.milesFromMetropolis)
train_data.loc[:,'yearsExperience']=(train_data.yearsExperience-np.mean(train_data.yearsExperience))/np.std(train_data.yearsExperience)
train_data.salary=np.log(train_data.salary)

XgBoost model¶

Need to one hot encode categorical variables. I refrain from using companyId as a feature since $63$ companies translates to $2^{63}$ features making learning unfeasible.

In [16]:
def one_hot_encode(data_frame,cat_cols):
    """
    This function one hot encodes those categorical variables which have cardinality less than or
    equal to unique_cols else uses feature hasher. The maximum cardinality of features created by the 
    featurehasher is 20. 
    """
    for col in cat_cols:
        gen_dummy_features = pd.get_dummies(data_frame[col],prefix=col)
        data_frame.drop([col],inplace=True, axis=1)
        data_frame=pd.concat([data_frame, gen_dummy_features],axis=1)
    
    return data_frame

Conclusions¶

  • XgBoost is the best performing model despite company Id not being included as a feature.
  • Catboost provides us the evidence for company being a redudant feature.
  • This makes sense since companies in a single geographical region (I am inferring based on the size of the dataset) pay almost the same for a given role and given years of experience of the candidate.

Answers to the questions¶

Please answer the following questions.

  1. How long did it take you to solve the problem?
    • Including running time took me around 3.5 hours
  2. What software language and libraries did you use to solve the problem?
    • Python, XgBoost, sklearn, numpy,Catboost
  3. What steps did you take to prepare the data for the project? Was any cleaning necessary?
    • Removed rows with salary=0.
    • Applied log transform to the salary (label) column.
    • Standarized and centered the continous features.
    • One hot encoding for XgBoost model.
  4. What algorithmic method did you apply? Why? What other methods did you consider?
    • Iconsidered gradient boosted decision trees.
    • Applied two variants of GBDT i.e. XgBoost and CatBoost algorithms to create final predictive model.

  5. Describe how the algorithmic method that you chose works?

    • Gradient Boosted trees and variants such as XGBoost and CatBoost are ensemble decision tree based models which are built by fitting shrunken version of the trees to the residuals.

  6. What features did you use? Why?

    • For the XgBoost model I used all featurs except companyId since there are 63 companies which would result in 2^63 more features due to one hot encoding. All features were used for Catboost algorithm since it handles caregorical variables natively without needing to one hot encode the said categorical feature.
  7. How did you train your model? During training, what issues concerned you?
    • I used grid search CV to find the best model parameters for the XgBoost tree. I used the same parameters for the CatBoost model due paucity of time.
  8. How did you assess the accuracy of your predictions? Why did you choose that method? Would you consider any alternative approaches for assessing accuracy?
    • I used 4 metrics MAPE (mean absolute error), RMSE (root mean squared error), MAE (Mean absolute error) and Bias.
  9. Which features had the greatest impact on salary? How did you identify these to be most significant? Which features had the least impact on salary? How did you identify these?
    • Refer to the feature importances plot for the XgBoost model. Miles from metropolis is the most important feature. I guess this is linked to the cost of living being higher in the metros than in the outskirts. The next two important features are the year of experience and the industry.
